

Java 20 Features (Interview Important + Examples)

Java 20 is a non-LTS (short-term) release, mainly focused on preview features and improvements to earlier Java 19/17 features.

1. Scoped Values (Incubator) ⭐
...............................
Scoped Values are an alternative to ThreadLocal, designed for sharing immutable data across threads efficiently (especially with virtual threads).

Example
import java.lang.ScopedValue;

public class ScopedValueExample {

    static final ScopedValue<String> USER =
            ScopedValue.newInstance();

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ScopedValue.where(USER, "Sunil")
                .run(() -> {

                    System.out.println(
                            "User: " + USER.get());
                });
    }
}
Output
User: Sunil
Benefits

✔ Faster than ThreadLocal
✔ Works well with virtual threads
✔ Safer concurrency model

2. Pattern Matching for switch (4th Preview) ⭐
.............................................
Java 20 improves switch pattern matching (from Java 17 preview).

Example
static String process(Object obj) {

    return switch (obj) {

        case String s ->
                "String: " + s;

        case Integer i ->
                "Integer: " + i;

        case Double d ->
                "Double: " + d;

        default ->
                "Unknown";
    };
}
Output
String: Java
Benefits

✔ Cleaner code
✔ No instanceof needed
✔ Better type handling

3. Record Patterns (Preview) ⭐
.......................................
Used to deconstruct records directly.

Example
record Employee(int id, String name) {}

static void print(Object obj) {

    if (obj instanceof Employee(int id, String name)) {

        System.out.println(id);
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}
Benefits

✔ Easy data extraction
✔ Works well with pattern matching

4. Virtual Threads (2nd Preview – JDK 20) ⭐
...........................................................
Virtual threads are lightweight threads for massive concurrency (finalized later in Java 21).

Example
Thread.startVirtualThread(() -> {

    System.out.println("Virtual Thread");
});
Real-Time Use Case
Banking System → 1 million requests
Virtual threads handle efficiently without heavy OS threads
5. Structured Concurrency (Incubator)
..................................................
Simplifies managing multiple threads as a single unit.

Example
try (var scope =
        new StructuredTaskScope.ShutdownOnFailure()) {

    var task1 = scope.fork(() -> "Task1");
    var task2 = scope.fork(() -> "Task2");

    scope.join();

    System.out.println(task1.get());
    System.out.println(task2.get());
}
Benefits

✔ Easier thread management
✔ Better error handling
✔ Cleaner concurrent code

6. Foreign Function & Memory API (2nd Preview)
.......................................................
Used to interact with native code (C/C++) safely.

Benefits

✔ Replaces JNI complexity
✔ Faster native integration
✔ Safer memory access

Real-Time Example (Spring Boot Concept)
Virtual Threads for API calls
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {

    Thread.startVirtualThread(() -> {

        System.out.println(
                "Processing request");
    });
}
Benefit

Handles thousands of concurrent requests efficiently
